  <h1>About</h1>

  <p>I'm Shukri Nur — most people call me Shay. I'm a graduate student in Health Informatics and Health Information Management at Dakota State University, where I'm a Dr. Richard Merkin Scholar, and I'm based in Columbus, Ohio.</p>

  <p>My path into health informatics ran through direct service. I spent years working face-to-face with patients — HIV case management in the Ryan White Program, chronic disease patient navigation at a community health center, community health work, and educational support roles. Working bilingually in English and Somali, I saw again and again how much of a person's health was decided outside the clinic: by housing, food access, language, insurance, and the neighborhoods they came home to.</p>

  <p>That's what pulled me toward the <em>social determinants of health</em> as a research focus. Now I work at the intersection of health data and health equity — assessing behavioral health data landscapes, analyzing how food environments relate to chronic disease, and mapping where chronic conditions and coverage gaps overlap across communities. I want to build health information systems that make inequity visible instead of burying it in averages.</p>

  <p>Longer term, I'm working toward doctoral study in social determinants of health research and a career in global public health. Outside of research, I read widely — public health, socioeconomics, and literature — and you can see what's on my shelf on the <a href="reading.html">Reading</a> page.</p>

